{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01LYbZEeWz23dChHd66Hz2LV","type":"tool_result","content":"1\t---\n2\tstepsCompleted: [1, 2, 3, 4]\n3\tstatus: complete\n4\tinputDocuments:\n5\t  - prd.md (multi-framework orchestration PRD, 2026-04-03)\n6\t  - architecture-multi-framework.md (multi-framework architecture, 2026-04-03)\n7\t---\n8\t\n9\t# codeharness - Epic Breakdown (Multi-Framework Orchestration)\n10\t\n11\t## Overview\n12\t\n13\tThis document provides the complete epic and story breakdown for codeharness multi-framework orchestration, decomposing the requirements from the PRD and Architecture into implementable stories.\n14\t\n15\t## Requirements Inventory\n16\t\n17\t### Functional Requirements\n18\t\n19\t- FR1: System can register and resolve agent drivers by name (claude-code, codex, opencode)\n20\t- FR2: System can detect whether a driver's CLI binary is installed and accessible on the system PATH\n21\t- FR3: System can verify a driver's authentication status before task dispatch\n22\t- FR4: System can report missing or unauthenticated drivers with install/auth instructions at workflow start\n23\t- FR5: System can spawn an agent process via the appropriate driver's CLI invocation\n24\t- FR6: System can terminate a running driver process on task timeout, cancellation, or circuit breaker\n25\t- FR7: Each driver can parse its framework's CLI output into the common StreamEvent protocol\n26\t- FR8: System can capture cost information from driver output and normalize to cost_usd\n27\t- FR9: System can classify driver errors into standard categories (RATE_LIMIT, NETWORK, AUTH, TIMEOUT, UNKNOWN)\n28\t- FR10: System can detect and report when a driver's output format is unparseable\n29\t- FR11: User can specify a driver field per task in workflow YAML (optional, defaults to claude-code)\n30\t- FR12: User can specify a model field per task in workflow YAML (optional, overrides agent default)\n31\t- FR13: System can resolve the effective model for a task via the resolution chain: task model → agent model → driver default\n32\t- FR14: System can validate workflow YAML referential integrity — all referenced drivers exist, all referenced agents exist\n33\t- FR15: System can load existing workflows without driver/model fields with full backward compatibility\n34\t- FR16: System can execute a workflow where consecutive tasks use different drivers\n35\t- FR17: System can serialize a task's output contract to a structured JSON file after task completion\n36\t- FR18: System can load a previous task's output contract and inject it as context into the next task's prompt\n37\t- FR19: System can pass acceptance criteria, changed file lists, and test results across framework boundaries via output contracts\n38\t- FR20: System can execute verification tasks on a different framework than implementation tasks within the same story\n39\t- FR21: User can configure gstack skills to load within claude-code driver sessions via workflow or agent config\n40\t- FR22: User can configure omo agents to load within opencode driver sessions via workflow or agent config\n41\t- FR23: System can pass plugin-specific configuration to the driver's CLI invocation\n42\t- FR24: System can render a schematic workflow graph in the Ink TUI showing all tasks as nodes with directional flow\n43\t- FR25: System can highlight the currently executing task node in the workflow graph\n44\t- FR26: System can display the driver name (framework label) under each task node in the workflow graph\n45\t- FR27: System can display accumulated cost and elapsed time per completed task node\n46\t- FR28: System can render loop blocks in the workflow graph with visual grouping and iteration counter\n47\t- FR29: System can update the workflow graph position within 500ms of a task transition\n48\t- FR30: System can show task completion status (checkmark, spinner, pending) per node in the workflow graph\n49\t- FR31: System can display stream events from any driver in the activity section\n50\t- FR32: System can display the active driver name alongside tool activity\n51\t- FR33: System can display per-story cost breakdown by driver in the story breakdown section\n52\t- FR34: System can accumulate cost per driver across a workflow run\n53\t- FR35: System can display total cost per driver in the TUI\n54\t- FR36: System can suggest a cheaper driver for tasks that don't require the capabilities of the configured driver\n55\t- FR37: System can document each driver's capabilities in a queryable format\n56\t- FR38: System can warn at workflow start if a task's requirements conflict with the driver's capabilities\n57\t\n58\t### Non-Functional Requirements\n59\t\n60\t- NFR1: Driver spawn (CLI cold start to first output) must complete within 3 seconds\n61\t- NFR2: TUI workflow graph position update must render within 500ms of task transition\n62\t- NFR3: Stream event parsing must keep up with driver output rate — no dropped events\n63\t- NFR4: Output contract serialization/deserialization must complete within 1 second for contracts up to 1MB\n64\t- NFR5: TUI render loop must maintain 15 FPS maximum without CPU spikes\n65\t- NFR6: Driver health check (all drivers in workflow) must complete within 5 seconds at workflow start\n66\t- NFR7: Codex driver must work with Codex CLI versions pinned in package.json\n67\t- NFR8: OpenCode driver must work with OpenCode CLI versions pinned in package.json\n68\t- NFR9: Claude Code driver must maintain compatibility with Agent SDK pinned version\n69\t- NFR10: Output contract JSON format must be stable across driver versions\n70\t- NFR11: Workflow YAML schema changes must be backward compatible\n71\t- NFR12: Plugin ecosystem integration must not require modifications to the plugins themselves\n72\t- NFR13: If a driver process crashes mid-task, the engine must detect it within 5 seconds\n73\t- NFR14: If a driver's CLI output format is unparseable, the engine must surface the raw output for debugging\n74\t- NFR15: Output contract files must survive engine crashes — written atomically\n75\t- NFR16: Driver timeout must be configurable per task (default: 30 minutes)\n76\t- NFR17: TUI must remain responsive during driver failures\n77\t- NFR18: Workflow engine must be idempotent for re-runs — resume from last completed task\n78\t\n79\t### Additional Requirements (from Architecture)\n80\t\n81\t- Existing AgentDriver interface must be refactored to use AsyncIterable<StreamEvent> instead of spawn()/AgentProcess\n82\t- Claude Code driver refactored from existing agent-dispatch.ts into driver class\n83\t- Driver factory pattern with explicit registration (no auto-discovery)\n84\t- Output contracts stored in .codeharness/contracts/{taskName}-{storyId}.json with atomic writes\n85\t- Model resolution chain: task → agent → driver default (3-level cascade)\n86\t- WorkflowGraph Ink component inserted between Header and StoryBreakdown\n87\t- Plugin pass-through via plugins array in workflow YAML task definition\n88\t- All drivers must follow identical class structure per architecture implementation patterns\n89\t- Fixture-based testing required for all drivers (real CLI output samples)\n90\t\n91\t### FR Coverage Map\n92\t\n93\t| FR | Epic | Description |\n94\t|----|------|-------------|\n95\t| FR1 | Epic 1 | Register and resolve drivers by name |\n96\t| FR2 | Epic 3 | Detect CLI binary on PATH |\n97\t| FR3 | Epic 3 | Verify driver auth status |\n98\t| FR4 | Epic 3 | Report missing drivers with install instructions |\n99\t| FR5 | Epic 1, 3 | Spawn agent process via driver CLI |\n100\t| FR6 | Epic 1 | Terminate driver on timeout/cancellation |\n101\t| FR7 | Epic 1, 3 | Parse CLI output to StreamEvent |\n102\t| FR8 | Epic 1, 3 | Capture and normalize cost_usd |\n103\t| FR9 | Epic 1, 3 | Classify driver errors into standard categories |\n104\t| FR10 | Epic 1, 3 | Detect and report unparseable output |\n105\t| FR11 | Epic 2 | Per-task driver field in workflow YAML |\n106\t| FR12 | Epic 2 | Per-task model field in workflow YAML |\n107\t| FR13 | Epic 1, 2 | Model resolution chain |\n108\t| FR14 | Epic 2 | Workflow YAML referential integrity |\n109\t| FR15 | Epic 1, 2 | Backward compatibility for old workflows |\n110\t| FR16 | Epic 4 | Execute workflow with different drivers per task |\n111\t| FR17 | Epic 4 | Serialize output contract to JSON |\n112\t| FR18 | Epic 4 | Load and inject output contract into next task |\n113\t| FR19 | Epic 4 | Pass ACs, files, tests across framework boundaries |\n114\t| FR20 | Epic 4 | Verification on different framework than implementation |\n115\t| FR21 | Epic 6 | Configure gstack skills in claude-code sessions |\n116\t| FR22 | Epic 6 | Configure omo agents in opencode sessions |\n117\t| FR23 | Epic 6 | Pass plugin config to driver CLI invocation |\n118\t| FR24 | Epic 5 | Render workflow graph in TUI |\n119\t| FR25 | Epic 5 | Highlight current task node |\n120\t| FR26 | Epic 5 | Display driver name under each node |\n121\t| FR27 | Epic 5 | Display cost/time per completed node |\n122\t| FR28 | Epic 5 | Render loop blocks with iteration counter |\n123\t| FR29 | Epic 5 | Update position within 500ms |\n124\t| FR30 | Epic 5 | Show completion status per node |\n125\t| FR31 | Epic 5 | Display stream events from any driver |\n126\t| FR32 | Epic 5 | Display active driver name in activity |\n127\t| FR33 | Epic 5 | Per-story cost breakdown by driver |\n128\t| FR34 | Epic 6 | Accumulate cost per driver |\n129\t| FR35 | Epic 6 | Display total cost per driver in TUI |\n130\t| FR36 | Epic 6 | Suggest cheaper driver (routing hint) |\n131\t| FR37 | Epic 6 | Driver capabilities in queryable format |\n132\t| FR38 | Epic 6 | Warn on task/driver capability conflicts |\n133\t\n134\t## Epic List\n135\t\n136\t### Epic 1: Driver Interface & Claude Code Refactor\n137\tUsers can run workflows using the formalized driver abstraction, with the existing Claude Code Agent SDK refactored into a proper driver class. Everything works exactly as before, but through the new AgentDriver interface.\n138\t**FRs covered:** FR1, FR5, FR6, FR7, FR8, FR9, FR10, FR13, FR15\n139\t\n140\t### Epic 2: Workflow Schema & Model Resolution\n141\tUsers can configure driver and model per task in workflow YAML. The workflow engine resolves models via the 3-level cascade and validates referential integrity. Backward compatible.\n142\t**FRs covered:** FR11, FR12, FR13, FR14, FR15\n143\t\n144\t### Epic 3: Codex & OpenCode Drivers\n145\tUsers can dispatch tasks to Codex CLI and OpenCode CLI. Both drivers implement AgentDriver, parse CLI output to StreamEvent, and handle health checks.\n146\t**FRs covered:** FR2, FR3, FR4, FR5, FR7, FR8, FR9, FR10\n147\t\n148\t### Epic 4: Cross-Framework Execution & Output Contracts\n149\tUsers can run workflows where consecutive tasks use different frameworks, with output contracts passing context between them. Cross-framework verification works end-to-end.\n150\t**FRs covered:** FR16, FR17, FR18, FR19, FR20\n151\t\n152\t### Epic 5: TUI Workflow Visualization\n153\tUsers can see the workflow graph in the TUI with current position, driver labels, cost/time per node, and loop counters. Activity display shows which driver is active.\n154\t**FRs covered:** FR24, FR25, FR26, FR27, FR28, FR29, FR30, FR31, FR32, FR33\n155\t\n156\t### Epic 6: Plugin Ecosystem & Cost Intelligence\n157\tUsers can configure gstack/omo plugins per task, see cost breakdowns per driver, and get routing hints for cheaper alternatives. Driver capability matrix warns about conflicts.\n158\t**FRs covered:** FR21, FR22, FR23, FR34, FR35, FR36, FR37, FR38\n159\t\n160\t## Epic 1: Driver Interface & Claude Code Refactor\n161\t\n162\tUsers can run workflows using the formalized driver abstraction, with the existing Claude Code Agent SDK refactored into a proper driver class.\n163\t\n164\t### Story 1.1: AgentDriver Interface & Types\n165\t\n166\tAs a developer,\n167\tI want a formalized AgentDriver interface with DriverHealth, DispatchOpts, and StreamEvent types,\n168\tSo that all drivers implement a consistent contract.\n169\t\n170\t**Acceptance Criteria:**\n171\t\n172\t**Given** the existing `src/lib/agents/types.ts`\n173\t**When** the interface is refactored\n174\t**Then** `AgentDriver` has `name`, `defaultModel`, `capabilities`, `healthCheck()`, `dispatch()`, `getLastCost()` methods\n175\t**And** `DispatchOpts` includes `prompt`, `model`, `cwd`, `sourceAccess`, `plugins`, `timeout`, `outputContract`\n176\t**And** `DriverHealth` includes `available`, `authenticated`, `version`, `error`\n177\t**And** `dispatch()` returns `AsyncIterable<StreamEvent>`\n178\t**And** all existing StreamEvent types are preserved\n179\t\n180\t### Story 1.2: Driver Factory & Registry\n181\t\n182\tAs a developer,\n183\tI want a driver factory that registers and resolves drivers by name,\n184\tSo that the workflow engine can get any driver without knowing its implementation.\n185\t\n186\t**Acceptance Criteria:**\n187\t\n188\t**Given** a new `src/lib/agents/drivers/factory.ts`\n189\t**When** `getDriver('claude-code')` is called\n190\t**Then** it returns the registered ClaudeCodeDriver instance\n191\t**And** `getDriver('unknown')` throws a descriptive error\n192\t**And** `listDrivers()` returns all registered driver names\n193\t**And** drivers are registered explicitly (no auto-discovery)\n194\t\n195\t### Story 1.3: Claude Code Driver Extraction\n196\t\n197\tAs a developer,\n198\tI want the existing Agent SDK dispatch logic extracted into a ClaudeCodeDriver class,\n199\tSo that Claude Code works through the same driver interface as future drivers.\n200\t\n201\t**Acceptance Criteria:**\n202\t\n203\t**Given** the existing `agent-dispatch.ts` dispatch logic\n204\t**When** refactored into `src/lib/agents/drivers/claude-code.ts`\n205\t**Then** `ClaudeCodeDriver` implements `AgentDriver` interface\n206\t**And** `dispatch()` calls Agent SDK `query()` and yields `StreamEvent` objects\n207\t**And** `healthCheck()` returns `{ available: true, authenticated: true }`\n208\t**And** `getLastCost()` returns cost from the last Agent SDK dispatch\n209\t**And** error classification maps Agent SDK errors to RATE_LIMIT, NETWORK, AUTH, TIMEOUT, UNKNOWN\n210\t**And** existing workflow execution produces identical results through the driver\n211\t\n212\t### Story 1.4: Model Resolution Module\n213\t\n214\tAs a developer,\n215\tI want a model resolver that cascades task → agent → driver defaults,\n216\tSo that the effective model for any task dispatch is deterministic.\n217\t\n218\t**Acceptance Criteria:**\n219\t\n220\t**Given** a new `src/lib/agents/model-resolver.ts`\n221\t**When** `resolveModel(task, agent, driver)` is called\n222\t**Then** task-level model takes highest priority\n223\t**And** agent-level model is used if task has no model\n224\t**And** driver default model is used if neither task nor agent specify one\n225\t**And** the resolved model is returned as a string\n226\t**And** backward compatible with existing workflows that have no model field\n227\t\n228\t### Story 1.5: Workflow Engine Driver Integration\n229\t\n230\tAs a developer,\n231\tI want the workflow engine to dispatch tasks through the driver factory,\n232\tSo that switching drivers is a configuration change, not a code change.\n233\t\n234\t**Acceptance Criteria:**\n235\t\n236\t**Given** the existing `workflow-engine.ts`\n237\t**When** executing a workflow task\n238\t**Then** the engine resolves the driver from the factory (defaulting to `claude-code`)\n239\t**And** the engine calls `driver.dispatch(opts)` instead of `dispatchAgent()` directly\n240\t**And** the engine consumes `AsyncIterable<StreamEvent>` from the driver\n241\t**And** existing workflows without `driver` field work identically\n242\t**And** driver process termination works on timeout/cancellation\n243\t\n244\t## Epic 2: Workflow Schema & Model Resolution\n245\t\n246\tUsers can configure driver and model per task in workflow YAML with backward compatibility.\n247\t\n248\t### Story 2.1: Workflow Schema Extension\n249\t\n250\tAs a user,\n251\tI want to specify `driver` and `model` per task in my workflow YAML,\n252\tSo that I can control which framework and model each task uses.\n253\t\n254\t**Acceptance Criteria:**\n255\t\n256\t**Given** `src/schemas/workflow.schema.json`\n257\t**When** updated with `driver`, `model`, and `plugins` fields on task definition\n258\t**Then** `driver` is optional with default `claude-code`\n259\t**And** `model` is optional with no default (falls through to resolution chain)\n260\t**And** `plugins` is optional array of strings\n261\t**And** existing workflows without these fields validate successfully\n262\t**And** `workflow-parser.ts` parses the new fields from YAML\n263\t\n264\t### Story 2.2: Workflow Referential Integrity Validation\n265\t\n266\tAs a user,\n267\tI want the workflow parser to validate that all referenced drivers and agents exist,\n268\tSo that I get clear errors before execution if my config is wrong.\n269\t\n270\t**Acceptance Criteria:**\n271\t\n272\t**Given** a workflow YAML with `driver: codex` on a task\n273\t**When** the workflow is parsed and validated\n274\t**Then** the parser checks that `codex` is a registered driver name\n275\t**And** the parser checks that all referenced agent names exist in agent templates\n276\t**And** validation errors include the specific field, task name, and suggested fix\n277\t**And** validation runs at parse time before any task dispatch\n278\t\n279\t## Epic 3: Codex & OpenCode Drivers\n280\t\n281\tUsers can dispatch tasks to Codex CLI and OpenCode CLI with full health checking.\n282\t\n283\t### Story 3.1: Codex Driver Implementation\n284\t\n285\tAs a user,\n286\tI want to run tasks on OpenAI Codex by setting `driver: codex`,\n287\tSo that I can use Codex models for implementation or verification.\n288\t\n289\t**Acceptance Criteria:**\n290\t\n291\t**Given** a new `src/lib/agents/drivers/codex.ts`\n292\t**When** `dispatch()` is called\n293\t**Then** the driver spawns `codex` CLI via `child_process.spawn`\n294\t**And** stdout is parsed line-by-line into `StreamEvent` objects\n295\t**And** unparseable lines are logged at debug level and skipped\n296\t**And** a `result` event is always yielded at the end (even on error)\n297\t**And** cost is captured from CLI output or set to `null`\n298\t**And** `healthCheck()` checks `which codex`, version, and auth status\n299\t**And** missing binary returns `{ available: false, error: \"codex CLI not found. Install: npm install -g @openai/codex\" }`\n300\t**And** fixture-based tests exist in `test/fixtures/drivers/codex/`\n301\t\n302\t### Story 3.2: OpenCode Driver Implementation\n303\t\n304\tAs a user,\n305\tI want to run tasks on OpenCode by setting `driver: opencode`,\n306\tSo that I can use OpenCode's multi-model support for any task.\n307\t\n308\t**Acceptance Criteria:**\n309\t\n310\t**Given** a new `src/lib/agents/drivers/opencode.ts`\n311\t**When** `dispatch()` is called\n312\t**Then** the driver spawns `opencode` CLI via `child_process.spawn`\n313\t**And** stdout is parsed line-by-line into `StreamEvent` objects\n314\t**And** unparseable lines are logged at debug level and skipped\n315\t**And** a `result` event is always yielded at the end (even on error)\n316\t**And** cost is captured from CLI output or set to `null`\n317\t**And** `healthCheck()` checks `which opencode`, version, and auth status\n318\t**And** missing binary returns `{ available: false, error: \"opencode not found. Install: https://opencode.ai\" }`\n319\t**And** fixture-based tests exist in `test/fixtures/drivers/opencode/`\n320\t\n321\t### Story 3.3: Driver Health Check at Workflow Start\n322\t\n323\tAs a user,\n324\tI want all referenced drivers health-checked before any task executes,\n325\tSo that I get immediate feedback if a CLI is missing or unauthenticated.\n326\t\n327\t**Acceptance Criteria:**\n328\t\n329\t**Given** a workflow referencing drivers `claude-code` and `codex`\n330\t**When** `codeharness run` starts\n331\t**Then** the engine calls `healthCheck()` on every unique driver in the workflow\n332\t**And** all health checks complete within 5 seconds total (NFR6)\n333\t**And** if any driver is unavailable, the run aborts with a clear error listing all failing drivers\n334\t**And** if all drivers are healthy, the run proceeds normally\n335\t\n336\t## Epic 4: Cross-Framework Execution & Output Contracts\n337\t\n338\tUsers can run workflows where consecutive tasks use different frameworks with data passing between them.\n339\t\n340\t### Story 4.1: Output Contract Schema & Serialization\n341\t\n342\tAs a developer,\n343\tI want output contracts serialized as JSON files with atomic writes,\n344\tSo that task results survive crashes and can be read by the next task.\n345\t\n346\t**Acceptance Criteria:**\n347\t\n348\t**Given** a new `src/lib/agents/output-contract.ts` and `src/schemas/output-contract.schema.json`\n349\t**When** a task completes\n350\t**Then** the engine writes a contract to `.codeharness/contracts/{taskName}-{storyId}.json`\n351\t**And** the write is atomic (write to `.tmp`, then rename)\n352\t**And** the contract includes version, taskName, storyId, driver, model, timestamp, cost_usd, duration_ms, changedFiles, testResults, output, acceptanceCriteria\n353\t**And** fields that aren't available are set to `null`\n354\t**And** serialization/deserialization completes within 1 second for contracts up to 1MB (NFR4)\n355\t\n356\t### Story 4.2: Output Contract Prompt Injection\n357\t\n358\tAs a developer,\n359\tI want the previous task's output contract injected into the next task's prompt,\n360\tSo that cross-framework tasks have context from the previous step.\n361\t\n362\t**Acceptance Criteria:**\n363\t\n364\t**Given** a completed task with a written output contract\n365\t**When** the next task in the workflow starts\n366\t**Then** the engine reads the previous contract and formats it as structured prompt context\n367\t**And** the prompt includes changed files, test results, output summary, AC statuses\n368\t**And** the injection is framework-agnostic\n369\t**And** if no previous contract exists (first task), no injection occurs\n370\t\n371\t### Story 4.3: Cross-Framework Workflow Execution\n372\t\n373\tAs a user,\n374\tI want to run a workflow where implement uses claude-code and verify uses codex,\n375\tSo that verification is structurally independent from implementation.\n376\t\n377\t**Acceptance Criteria:**\n378\t\n379\t**Given** a workflow with `implement: { driver: claude-code }` and `verify: { driver: codex }`\n380\t**When** `codeharness run` executes\n381\t**Then** the implement task runs via Claude Code driver\n382\t**And** on completion, an output contract is written\n383\t**And** the verify task starts via Codex driver with the output contract injected\n384\t**And** loop blocks correctly alternate between drivers\n385\t**And** the workflow engine resumes from the last completed task on re-run (NFR18)\n386\t\n387\t## Epic 5: TUI Workflow Visualization\n388\t\n389\tUsers can see the workflow graph in the TUI with current position, driver labels, cost/time, and loop counters.\n390\t\n391\t### Story 5.1: WorkflowGraph Component\n392\t\n393\tAs a user,\n394\tI want to see a schematic workflow graph in the TUI,\n395\tSo that I can see all tasks, their order, and loop blocks at a glance.\n396\t\n397\t**Acceptance Criteria:**\n398\t\n399\t**Given** a new `src/lib/ink-workflow.tsx`\n400\t**When** a workflow is running\n401\t**Then** the TUI renders a workflow graph between Header and StoryBreakdown\n402\t**And** each task is shown as a node with its name\n403\t**And** nodes are connected with `→` arrows\n404\t**And** loop blocks are rendered as `loop(N)[ task1 → task2 ]` with iteration count\n405\t**And** the component receives `flow`, `currentTask`, and `taskStates` as props\n406\t\n407\t### Story 5.2: Task Status & Driver Labels\n408\t\n409\tAs a user,\n410\tI want each workflow node to show its status, driver, and cost,\n411\tSo that I can see what's running, on which framework, and what it costs.\n412\t\n413\t**Acceptance Criteria:**\n414\t\n415\t**Given** the WorkflowGraph component\n416\t**When** a task is pending → dim text\n417\t**And** when active → cyan + spinner\n418\t**And** when done → green ✓\n419\t**And** when failed → red ✗\n420\t**And** the driver name is displayed dimmed below each node\n421\t**And** cost and elapsed time are displayed below driver name for completed nodes\n422\t**And** the graph updates within 500ms of task transition (NFR2)\n423\t\n424\t### Story 5.3: Activity Display Driver Integration\n425\t\n426\tAs a user,\n427\tI want to see which driver is active in the tool activity section,\n428\tSo that I know which framework is executing the current tool call.\n429\t\n430\t**Acceptance Criteria:**\n431\t\n432\t**Given** the existing activity display components\n433\t**When** stream events arrive from any driver\n434\t**Then** the active driver name is shown alongside tool activity\n435\t**And** per-story cost breakdown shows cost by driver\n436\t**And** the TUI remains responsive during driver failures (NFR17)\n437\t\n438\t## Epic 6: Plugin Ecosystem & Cost Intelligence\n439\t\n440\tUsers can configure gstack/omo plugins, track costs per driver, and get capability warnings.\n441\t\n442\t### Story 6.1: Plugin Pass-Through Configuration\n443\t\n444\tAs a user,\n445\tI want to specify plugins per task in workflow YAML,\n446\tSo that gstack skills load in Claude Code sessions and omo agents load in OpenCode sessions.\n447\t\n448\t**Acceptance Criteria:**\n449\t\n450\t**Given** a workflow task with `plugins: ['gstack']` on a claude-code driver\n451\t**When** the driver dispatches the task\n452\t**Then** the driver translates the plugin config to framework-specific CLI flags\n453\t**And** codex driver warns and ignores unsupported plugins\n454\t**And** plugin configuration does not require modifying the plugins themselves (NFR12)\n455\t\n456\t### Story 6.2: Cost Tracking Per Driver\n457\t\n458\tAs a user,\n459\tI want to see accumulated cost per driver across a workflow run,\n460\tSo that I can compare framework costs and optimize.\n461\t\n462\t**Acceptance Criteria:**\n463\t\n464\t**Given** a multi-driver workflow run\n465\t**When** tasks complete on different drivers\n466\t**Then** the engine accumulates cost per driver\n467\t**And** total cost per driver is displayed in the TUI\n468\t**And** drivers that don't report cost show `null` (not $0)\n469\t\n470\t### Story 6.3: Driver Capability Matrix & Routing Hints\n471\t\n472\tAs a user,\n473\tI want the system to warn me about capability conflicts and suggest cheaper alternatives,\n474\tSo that I avoid misconfigurations and optimize costs.\n475\t\n476\t**Acceptance Criteria:**\n477\t\n478\t**Given** driver capabilities defined in `factory.ts`\n479\t**When** a workflow starts\n480\t**Then** the engine warns if a task's requirements conflict with the driver's capabilities\n481\t**And** `codeharness drivers` CLI command outputs capabilities as structured JSON\n482\t**And** when a task's driver costs >2x the cheapest capable alternative, an advisory message is displayed\n483\t"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_01RMnci4JBW5N3n4PYpHDPEs","session_id":"576f74f4-0d7f-4316-a569-4c3ab5c122fd","uuid":"31c0bdb8-3f5a-4269-9543-42f4764c3fb3","timestamp":"2026-04-03T08:50:31.125Z"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01GyQLSds7bgYQosLc6tZzGR","type":"tool_result","content":"1\t---\n2\tstepsCompleted: [1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6, 7, 8]\n3\tlastStep: 8\n4\tstatus: 'complete'\n5\tcompletedAt: '2026-04-03'\n6\tinputDocuments:\n7\t  - prd.md (multi-framework orchestration PRD, 2026-04-03)\n8\t  - architecture.md (existing v1 architecture, brownfield context)\n9\t  - prd-validation-report.md (validation report, 4.5/5 Pass)\n10\tworkflowType: 'architecture'\n11\tproject_name: 'codeharness'\n12\tuser_name: 'BMad'\n13\tdate: '2026-04-03'\n14\t---\n15\t\n16\t# Architecture Decision Document\n17\t\n18\t_This document builds collaboratively through step-by-step discovery. Sections are appended as we work through each architectural decision together._\n19\t\n20\t## Project Context Analysis\n21\t\n22\t### Requirements Overview\n23\t\n24\t**Functional Requirements:**\n25\t38 FRs across 9 capability areas. The core is a driver abstraction layer (FR1-FR10) that normalizes 3 agent framework CLIs into a common `AgentDriver` interface with `StreamEvent` output. The workflow engine gains per-task `driver` and `model` fields (FR11-FR15). Cross-framework task execution uses explicit output contracts serialized as JSON (FR16-FR20). The Ink TUI gains a workflow graph component (FR24-FR30). Plugin ecosystem integration (gstack/omo) passes config to parent driver CLIs (FR21-FR23).\n26\t\n27\t**Non-Functional Requirements:**\n28\t18 NFRs across performance (driver spawn <3s, TUI update <500ms, health check <5s), integration (pinned CLI versions, backward-compatible schema, no plugin modifications), and reliability (crash detection <5s, atomic contract writes, idempotent re-runs). Single-user local CLI — no scalability or availability requirements.\n29\t\n30\t**Scale & Complexity:**\n31\t\n32\t- Primary domain: Node.js CLI extending existing Commander.js architecture\n33\t- Complexity level: Medium — one new architectural layer (drivers) on proven foundation\n34\t- Estimated architectural components: ~8 new (3 drivers, 1 driver factory, 1 output contract module, 1 TUI workflow component, workflow schema extension, model resolver)\n35\t\n36\t### Technical Constraints & Dependencies\n37\t\n38\t- **Existing architecture** — 10 decisions from v1 architecture remain valid: CLI↔Plugin boundary, state management, beads integration, template embedding, verification pipeline. This PRD extends, not replaces.\n39\t- **Agent SDK** — Claude Code Agent SDK (`@anthropic-ai/claude-agent-sdk`) already in use for in-process dispatch. Stays as the claude-code driver implementation.\n40\t- **Codex CLI** — External binary (`codex`). Output format must be reverse-engineered from real CLI output. Auth via OpenAI API key or ChatGPT account.\n41\t- **OpenCode CLI** — External binary (`opencode`). Go-based. Output format must be reverse-engineered. Supports 75+ models with per-provider keys.\n42\t- **No programmatic SDK** — Neither Codex nor OpenCode expose a dispatch SDK. All integration is CLI wrapping via `child_process.spawn` with stdout/stderr parsing.\n43\t- **Ink/React TUI** — Existing TUI uses Ink 6 with React 19. New workflow graph component must fit the existing component architecture and 15 FPS render loop.\n44\t- **Workflow YAML schema** — Existing `workflow.schema.json` must be extended (not replaced) with `driver` and `model` fields. JSON Schema backward compatibility required.\n45\t\n46\t### Cross-Cutting Concerns Identified\n47\t\n48\t1. **Driver lifecycle management** — Spawning, monitoring, timeout, termination, crash recovery applies to all drivers. Must be uniform regardless of whether the driver is in-process (Agent SDK) or CLI-wrapped (Codex, OpenCode).\n49\t2. **Stream event normalization** — Every driver must produce `StreamEvent` objects. The TUI, cost tracker, and workflow engine all consume these. A driver that drops events or misparses output breaks everything downstream.\n50\t3. **Output contract integrity** — Cross-framework task execution depends on output contracts being complete, correctly serialized, and crash-safe. A corrupted contract means the next task gets garbage context.\n51\t4. **Model resolution cascade** — Task model → agent model → driver default must be consistent across workflow parsing, driver dispatch, and TUI display. A disagreement means the TUI shows one model while the driver uses another.\n52\t\n53\t## Starter Template Evaluation\n54\t\n55\t### Primary Technology Domain\n56\t\n57\tNode.js CLI tool — already built and running. TypeScript + tsup + Commander.js + Vitest. Ink 6 + React 19 for TUI. Published on npm as `codeharness`.\n58\t\n59\t### Starter Options Considered\n60\t\n61\t**N/A — Brownfield project.** The existing technology stack is established:\n62\t\n63\t- TypeScript strict mode, ESM modules\n64\t- tsup for build → `dist/`\n65\t- Commander.js for CLI parsing\n66\t- Vitest + c8 for testing/coverage\n67\t- BATS for bash integration tests\n68\t- Ink 6 + React 19 for terminal UI\n69\t- Claude Code Agent SDK for agent dispatch\n70\t\n71\t### Selected Starter: Existing codebase\n72\t\n73\t**Rationale:** No new project initialization needed. The multi-framework feature adds files to `src/lib/agents/drivers/`, extends `src/schemas/workflow.schema.json`, and adds Ink components to `src/lib/ink-*.tsx`. All within the established architecture.\n74\t\n75\t**New modules to add:**\n76\t\n77\t```\n78\tsrc/lib/agents/drivers/\n79\t├── claude-code.ts      # Refactor existing dispatchAgent() into driver interface\n80\t├── codex.ts            # New — wraps codex CLI\n81\t├── opencode.ts         # New — wraps opencode CLI\n82\t├── factory.ts          # New — driver registry and resolution\n83\t└── types.ts            # Existing — extend AgentDriver interface\n84\t\n85\tsrc/lib/\n86\t├── model-resolver.ts   # New — task → agent → driver default cascade\n87\t├── output-contract.ts  # New — serialize/deserialize cross-framework contracts\n88\t└── ink-workflow.tsx     # New — TUI workflow graph component\n89\t```\n90\t\n91\t**Note:** No project initialization story needed. First story is driver interface formalization.\n92\t\n93\t## Core Architectural Decisions\n94\t\n95\t### Decision 1: Driver Interface Design\n96\t\n97\t**Decision:** Refactor `AgentDriver` interface to support both in-process (Agent SDK) and CLI-wrapped drivers uniformly. `dispatch()` returns `AsyncIterable<StreamEvent>` instead of `spawn()` returning `AgentProcess`.\n98\t\n99\t**Interface:**\n100\t\n101\t```typescript\n102\texport interface AgentDriver {\n103\t  readonly name: string;\n104\t  readonly defaultModel: string;\n105\t  healthCheck(): Promise<DriverHealth>;\n106\t  dispatch(opts: DispatchOpts): AsyncIterable<StreamEvent>;\n107\t  getLastCost(): number | null;\n108\t}\n109\t\n110\tinterface DispatchOpts {\n111\t  prompt: string;\n112\t  model: string;\n113\t  cwd: string;\n114\t  sourceAccess: boolean;\n115\t  plugins?: string[];\n116\t  timeout?: number;\n117\t  outputContract?: OutputContract;\n118\t}\n119\t```\n120\t\n121\t**Rationale:** The workflow engine and TUI consume `StreamEvent` regardless of source. `AsyncIterable` unifies in-process (Agent SDK yields directly) and CLI-wrapped (stdout parsed into events) behind the same consumer interface. Adding new drivers requires implementing `dispatch()` and returning events — no engine changes.\n122\t\n123\t### Decision 2: CLI-Wrapping Strategy\n124\t\n125\t**Decision:** CLI drivers use `child_process.spawn` with stdout line parsing. No PTY allocation. JSON output mode preferred where available.\n126\t\n127\t**Pattern:** Spawn CLI binary with `stdio: ['ignore', 'pipe', 'pipe']`. Parse stdout line-by-line. Each line parsed into `StreamEvent` or null. Yield non-null events from `dispatch()`.\n128\t\n129\t**Health check:** Three-step: (1) `which <binary>` to check installation, (2) version/auth check command, (3) return `{ available, authenticated, version, error? }`.\n130\t\n131\t**Crash detection:** Monitor `proc.exitCode` via Node.js `close` event. Non-zero exit yields `result` event with error classification. Meets NFR13 (<5s detection) — `close` fires immediately.\n132\t\n133\t**Rationale:** No PTY avoids terminal emulation complexity. JSON output mode gives structured data. Line-by-line parsing is simple, streamable, and testable with fixture files.\n134\t\n135\t### Decision 3: Output Contract Format\n136\t\n137\t**Decision:** JSON files in `.codeharness/contracts/{taskName}-{storyId}.json`. Written atomically (write to `.tmp`, rename). Read by next task's prompt injection.\n138\t\n139\t**Contract structure:**\n140\t```json\n141\t{\n142\t  \"version\": 1,\n143\t  \"taskName\": \"implement\",\n144\t  \"storyId\": \"3-1\",\n145\t  \"driver\": \"claude-code\",\n146\t  \"model\": \"claude-opus-4\",\n147\t  \"timestamp\": \"2026-04-03T10:30:00Z\",\n148\t  \"cost_usd\": 0.42,\n149\t  \"duration_ms\": 240000,\n150\t  \"changedFiles\": [\"src/api/users.ts\", \"src/api/users.test.ts\"],\n151\t  \"testResults\": { \"passed\": 12, \"failed\": 0, \"coverage\": 98.5 },\n152\t  \"output\": \"Implementation complete...\",\n153\t  \"acceptanceCriteria\": [\n154\t    { \"id\": \"AC1\", \"description\": \"User can register\", \"status\": \"implemented\" }\n155\t  ]\n156\t}\n157\t```\n158\t\n159\t**Injection:** Workflow engine reads contract, appends structured summary to next task's prompt as context.\n160\t\n161\t**Rationale:** JSON is universal across drivers. Atomic writes (NFR15) prevent corruption on crash. Version field allows format evolution. Contracts are debuggable — plain files on disk.\n162\t\n163\t### Decision 4: Model Resolution\n164\t\n165\t**Decision:** Three-level cascade resolved at dispatch time by `model-resolver.ts`.\n166\t\n167\t**Resolution order:**\n168\t1. Task-level `model` in workflow YAML (highest priority)\n169\t2. Agent-level `model` in agent YAML\n170\t3. Driver default model (hard-coded per driver)\n171\t\n172\t**Driver defaults:**\n173\t- `claude-code`: `claude-sonnet-4-20250514`\n174\t- `codex`: `codex-mini`\n175\t- `opencode`: inherits from OpenCode's own config\n176\t\n177\t**Implementation:** `resolveModel(task, agent, driver) → task.model ?? agent.model ?? driver.defaultModel`\n178\t\n179\t**Rationale:** Simple, deterministic, debuggable. Resolved model is logged and displayed in TUI. No magic, no indirection.\n180\t\n181\t### Decision 5: TUI Workflow Graph Component\n182\t\n183\t**Decision:** New `WorkflowGraph` Ink component inserted between Header and StoryBreakdown. Renders a single-line flow with status indicators, driver labels, and cost/time per node.\n184\t\n185\t**Rendering format:**\n186\t```\n187\t━━━ Workflow: story 3-1 ━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━\n188\t  implement ✓  →  verify ◆  →  loop(1)[ retry → verify ]\n189\t  claude-code     codex\n190\t  $0.42 / 4m      ... / 2m\n191\t━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━\n192\t```\n193\t\n194\t**Status indicators:** pending (dim), active (cyan + spinner), done (green ✓), failed (red ✗). Loop blocks show iteration count.\n195\t\n196\t**Rationale:** Fits existing Ink component pattern. Single-line flow is readable for workflows up to ~5 tasks. Driver and cost info below each node gives full visibility at a glance.\n197\t\n198\t### Decision 6: Plugin Ecosystem Pass-Through\n199\t\n200\t**Decision:** Workflow YAML tasks specify a `plugins` array. Drivers translate to framework-specific CLI flags.\n201\t\n202\t**YAML:** `plugins: ['gstack']` on a claude-code task. `plugins: ['omo']` on an opencode task.\n203\t\n204\t**Driver translation:**\n205\t- `claude-code`: `plugins` → Agent SDK plugin options or `--plugin` flag\n206\t- `opencode`: `plugins` → `--plugin` flag\n207\t- `codex`: plugins not supported → warn and ignore\n208\t\n209\t**Rationale:** Declarative config in YAML. Drivers handle translation. No framework-specific knowledge leaks into the workflow engine.\n210\t\n211\t## Implementation Patterns & Consistency Rules\n212\t\n213\t### Critical Conflict Points\n214\t\n215\t5 areas where AI agents implementing different drivers could diverge:\n216\t\n217\t1. Driver file structure and exports\n218\t2. StreamEvent production from different CLI outputs\n219\t3. Error classification from framework-specific errors\n220\t4. Output contract population from different agent outputs\n221\t5. Health check implementation per driver\n222\t\n223\t### Driver Implementation Pattern\n224\t\n225\t**Every driver MUST follow this structure:**\n226\t\n227\t```typescript\n228\t// src/lib/agents/drivers/{name}.ts\n229\timport type { AgentDriver, DispatchOpts, StreamEvent, DriverHealth } from './types.js';\n230\t\n231\texport class CodexDriver implements AgentDriver {\n232\t  readonly name = 'codex';\n233\t  readonly defaultModel = 'codex-mini';\n234\t  private lastCost: number | null = null;\n235\t\n236\t  async healthCheck(): Promise<DriverHealth> { /* ... */ }\n237\t  async *dispatch(opts: DispatchOpts): AsyncIterable<StreamEvent> { /* ... */ }\n238\t  getLastCost(): number | null { return this.lastCost; }\n239\t}\n240\t```\n241\t\n242\t**Rules:**\n243\t- One file per driver, named `{driver-name}.ts`\n244\t- Class name: `{DriverName}Driver` (PascalCase)\n245\t- Export the class as named export\n246\t- Register in `factory.ts` — never auto-discover\n247\t- Driver MUST be stateless between dispatches (except `lastCost`)\n248\t\n249\t### StreamEvent Production Pattern\n250\t\n251\t**All drivers MUST produce events in this order for a successful dispatch:**\n252\t\n253\t1. Zero or more `tool-start` → `tool-input` → `tool-complete` sequences\n254\t2. Zero or more `text` events (interleaved with tool sequences)\n255\t3. Zero or more `retry` events (if API retries occur)\n256\t4. Exactly one `result` event at the end (with cost_usd and sessionId)\n257\t\n258\t**If the driver cannot map a CLI output line to a StreamEvent, it MUST:**\n259\t- Log the unparseable line at debug level\n260\t- Skip it (yield nothing)\n261\t- Never yield a malformed event\n262\t- Never throw — unparseable lines are expected during format discovery\n263\t\n264\t**Cost reporting:**\n265\t- If the CLI reports cost → set `result.cost_usd`\n266\t- If the CLI does not report cost → set `result.cost_usd = null` (not 0, not undefined)\n267\t\n268\t### Error Classification Pattern\n269\t\n270\t**All drivers MUST classify errors into exactly these categories:**\n271\t\n272\t```typescript\n273\ttype ErrorCategory = 'RATE_LIMIT' | 'NETWORK' | 'AUTH' | 'TIMEOUT' | 'UNKNOWN';\n274\t```\n275\t\n276\t**Classification rules (in priority order):**\n277\t1. HTTP 429 or \"rate limit\" in message → `RATE_LIMIT`\n278\t2. ECONNREFUSED, ETIMEDOUT, ENOTFOUND → `NETWORK`\n279\t3. HTTP 401/403 or \"unauthorized\"/\"forbidden\" → `AUTH`\n280\t4. Process killed by timeout → `TIMEOUT`\n281\t5. Everything else → `UNKNOWN`\n282\t\n283\t**Driver MUST NOT invent new categories.**\n284\t\n285\t### Output Contract Population Pattern\n286\t\n287\t**After each task dispatch, the workflow engine populates an output contract. Drivers MUST:**\n288\t\n289\t- Set `changedFiles` from file modification events (tool-complete for Write/Edit tools)\n290\t- Set `testResults` from parsed test output (if detectable) or `null`\n291\t- Set `output` as the agent's final text response\n292\t- Set `cost_usd` from `getLastCost()`\n293\t- Never fabricate data — if information isn't available, set `null`\n294\t\n295\t### Health Check Pattern\n296\t\n297\t**All drivers MUST implement:**\n298\t\n299\t```typescript\n300\tinterface DriverHealth {\n301\t  available: boolean;     // CLI binary found on PATH\n302\t  authenticated: boolean; // Auth check passed (or N/A)\n303\t  version: string | null; // CLI version string\n304\t  error?: string;         // Human-readable error if !available || !authenticated\n305\t}\n306\t```\n307\t\n308\t**Check sequence:** (1) `which {binary}`, (2) `{binary} --version`, (3) framework-specific auth check.\n309\t\n310\t**If binary not found:** Return with `error` containing install instructions.\n311\t\n312\t### Testing Pattern for Drivers\n313\t\n314\t**Every driver MUST have:**\n315\t- Unit tests with real CLI output fixtures in `test/fixtures/drivers/{name}/`\n316\t- Test that `dispatch()` produces correct `StreamEvent` sequence from fixture\n317\t- Test that `healthCheck()` handles binary-not-found gracefully\n318\t- Test that error classification works for framework-specific errors\n319\t\n320\t**Anti-pattern:** Never mock `child_process.spawn`. Mock at the line-reader level — feed fixture lines to `parseLine()`.\n321\t\n322\t### Enforcement Guidelines\n323\t\n324\t**Code review checklist for new drivers:**\n325\t1. Class implements `AgentDriver` interface? ✓\n326\t2. Registered in `factory.ts`? ✓\n327\t3. `dispatch()` yields events in correct order? ✓\n328\t4. `result` event always emitted (even on error)? ✓\n329\t5. Error classification uses standard categories? ✓\n330\t6. Fixture-based tests exist? ✓\n331\t\n332\t## Project Structure & Boundaries\n333\t\n334\t### New Files (Multi-Framework Extension)\n335\t\n336\t```\n337\tsrc/lib/agents/\n338\t├── drivers/\n339\t│   ├── types.ts              # Extended AgentDriver interface, DispatchOpts, DriverHealth\n340\t│   ├── factory.ts            # NEW — driver registry, getDriver(name), listDrivers()\n341\t│   ├── claude-code.ts        # REFACTOR — extract from agent-dispatch.ts into driver class\n342\t│   ├── codex.ts              # NEW — Codex CLI wrapper driver\n343\t│   └── opencode.ts           # NEW — OpenCode CLI wrapper driver\n344\t├── model-resolver.ts         # NEW — task → agent → driver default cascade\n345\t├── output-contract.ts        # NEW — serialize/deserialize, atomic write, prompt injection\n346\t└── stream-parser.ts          # EXISTING — shared line parsing utilities\n347\t\n348\tsrc/lib/\n349\t├── workflow-parser.ts        # MODIFY — add driver/model/plugins to task schema validation\n350\t├── workflow-engine.ts        # MODIFY — use driver factory, output contracts between tasks\n351\t├── agent-dispatch.ts         # MODIFY — delegate to driver.dispatch() instead of direct SDK\n352\t├── ink-workflow.tsx           # NEW — WorkflowGraph component\n353\t├── ink-components.tsx         # MODIFY — add WorkflowGraph to layout, extend SprintInfo\n354\t├── ink-app.tsx                # MODIFY — render WorkflowGraph between Header and StoryBreakdown\n355\t└── ink-renderer.tsx           # MODIFY — add updateWorkflowState() to RendererHandle\n356\t\n357\tsrc/schemas/\n358\t├── workflow.schema.json       # MODIFY — add driver, model, plugins to task definition\n359\t└── output-contract.schema.json # NEW — JSON Schema for output contract format\n360\t\n361\ttest/\n362\t├── unit/\n363\t│   ├── drivers/\n364\t│   │   ├── claude-code.test.ts\n365\t│   │   ├── codex.test.ts\n366\t│   │   ├── opencode.test.ts\n367\t│   │   ├── factory.test.ts\n368\t│   │   └── model-resolver.test.ts\n369\t│   ├── output-contract.test.ts\n370\t│   └── ink-workflow.test.tsx\n371\t└── fixtures/\n372\t    └── drivers/\n373\t        ├── codex/             # Real captured Codex CLI output samples\n374\t        │   ├── success.jsonl\n375\t        │   ├── error-rate-limit.txt\n376\t        │   └── error-auth.txt\n377\t        └── opencode/          # Real captured OpenCode CLI output samples\n378\t            ├── success.txt\n379\t            ├── error-network.txt\n380\t            └── error-auth.txt\n381\t\n382\t.codeharness/\n383\t└── contracts/                 # Runtime — output contract JSON files per task/story\n384\t```\n385\t\n386\t### Architectural Boundaries\n387\t\n388\t**Driver Boundary:**\n389\t- Drivers ONLY know how to spawn their CLI and parse output → `StreamEvent`\n390\t- Drivers do NOT know about workflows, stories, TUI, or other drivers\n391\t- The workflow engine consumes drivers via `AgentDriver` interface only\n392\t\n393\t**Workflow Engine Boundary:**\n394\t- Engine resolves drivers from factory, resolves models, dispatches tasks\n395\t- Engine writes/reads output contracts between tasks\n396\t- Engine does NOT parse CLI output or know driver internals\n397\t\n398\t**TUI Boundary:**\n399\t- TUI consumes `StreamEvent` and workflow state updates\n400\t- TUI does NOT dispatch drivers or write contracts\n401\t- `WorkflowGraph` component receives flow structure and task states as props\n402\t\n403\t**Output Contract Boundary:**\n404\t- Contracts are JSON files on disk — written by engine, read by engine\n405\t- Contracts are framework-agnostic — same schema regardless of source driver\n406\t- Contracts are injected as prompt context, not as structured API calls\n407\t\n408\t### FR to Structure Mapping\n409\t\n410\t| FR Capability Area | Files |\n411\t|-------------------|-------|\n412\t| Driver Management (FR1-FR6) | `drivers/factory.ts`, `drivers/types.ts`, each driver file |\n413\t| Stream Normalization (FR7-FR10) | Each driver's `parseLine()`, `stream-parser.ts` |\n414\t| Workflow Config (FR11-FR15) | `workflow-parser.ts`, `workflow.schema.json` |\n415\t| Cross-Framework Execution (FR16-FR20) | `output-contract.ts`, `workflow-engine.ts` |\n416\t| Plugin Integration (FR21-FR23) | Each driver's `dispatch()` (plugins → CLI flags) |\n417\t| TUI Workflow Graph (FR24-FR30) | `ink-workflow.tsx`, `ink-app.tsx`, `ink-components.tsx` |\n418\t| TUI Activity Extension (FR31-FR33) | `ink-renderer.tsx`, `ink-activity-components.tsx` |\n419\t| Cost Tracking (FR34-FR36) | `ink-renderer.tsx`, `ink-workflow.tsx` |\n420\t| Driver Capability Matrix (FR37-FR38) | `drivers/factory.ts` (capabilities metadata per driver) |\n421\t\n422\t### Data Flow\n423\t\n424\t```\n425\tWorkflow YAML → workflow-parser → resolved tasks with driver/model\n426\t    ↓\n427\tworkflow-engine → model-resolver → resolved model per task\n428\t    ↓\n429\tdriver-factory → get driver by name → driver.healthCheck()\n430\t    ↓\n431\tdriver.dispatch(opts) → AsyncIterable<StreamEvent>\n432\t    ↓\n433\t    ├→ ink-renderer.update(event) → TUI renders\n434\t    ├→ workflow-engine collects events → output-contract.write()\n435\t    └→ next task: output-contract.read() → inject into prompt\n436\t```\n437\t\n438\t## Architecture Validation Results\n439\t\n440\t### Coherence Validation ✓\n441\t\n442\t**Decision Compatibility:** All 6 decisions are internally consistent. `AsyncIterable<StreamEvent>` from Decision 1 feeds both workflow engine (Decision 3) and TUI (Decision 5). Model resolution (Decision 4) feeds `DispatchOpts.model` from Decision 1. Plugin pass-through (Decision 6) extends `DispatchOpts.plugins`. No contradictions.\n443\t\n444\t**Pattern Consistency:** All drivers follow identical class structure, registration, event ordering, and error classification. Output contracts are framework-agnostic by design.\n445\t\n446\t**Structure Alignment:** Project structure maps cleanly to decisions — `drivers/` for Decisions 1-2, `output-contract.ts` for Decision 3, `model-resolver.ts` for Decision 4, `ink-workflow.tsx` for Decision 5.\n447\t\n448\t### Requirements Coverage ✓\n449\t\n450\t**Functional Requirements:** 38/38 FRs architecturally supported. Every FR capability area maps to specific architectural decisions and source files.\n451\t\n452\t**Non-Functional Requirements:** 18/18 NFRs architecturally supported. Performance NFRs met by design choices (no PTY, Ink 15 FPS, atomic writes). Reliability NFRs met by Node.js close events, debug logging, and contract versioning.\n453\t\n454\t### Gap Analysis\n455\t\n456\t**Critical Gaps:** 0\n457\t\n458\t**Important Gaps (resolved):**\n459\t1. Added `capabilities: DriverCapabilities` to `AgentDriver` interface for FR37-FR38\n460\t2. Added `suggestCheaperDriver()` to `factory.ts` for FR36 cost routing hints\n461\t\n462\t### Architecture Completeness Checklist\n463\t\n464\t- [x] Project context analyzed (brownfield, 38 FRs, 18 NFRs)\n465\t- [x] 6 architectural decisions documented with rationale\n466\t- [x] Implementation patterns defined (driver structure, events, errors, contracts, health, testing)\n467\t- [x] Project structure mapped with FR traceability\n468\t- [x] Architectural boundaries defined (driver, engine, TUI, contract)\n469\t- [x] Data flow documented\n470\t- [x] All FRs and NFRs architecturally supported\n471\t\n472\t### Architecture Readiness Assessment\n473\t\n474\t**Overall Status:** READY FOR IMPLEMENTATION\n475\t**Confidence Level:** High\n476\t\n477\t**First Implementation Priority:** Formalize `AgentDriver` interface and refactor existing Agent SDK dispatch into `ClaudeCodeDriver` class.\n478\t"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_01RMnci4JBW5N3n4PYpHDPEs","session_id":"576f74f4-0d7f-4316-a569-4c3ab5c122fd","uuid":"8c8fd19a-35a6-46f7-bcf7-db3d66c588f4","timestamp":"2026-04-03T08:50:31.232Z"}
